HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1397
By Atchley
A RESOLUTION to honor Judge Rex Henry Ogle on the occasion
of his retirement from the bench of the Fourth
Judicial District.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly take great pleasure in recognizing
the longest serving judge in the history of the Fourth Judicial District, namely the Honorable Rex
Henry Ogle; and
WHEREAS, Judge Ogle is taking a much-deserved retirement after thirty-six years of
hearing both criminal and civil cases in the district's Circuit Court; and
WHEREAS, Judge Ogle has earned the unqualified respect of members of the bar and
bench alike during his remarkable tenure, and he has rendered thoughtful service to his peers
as the Presiding Judge of the Fourth Judicial District during six separate terms; and
WHEREAS, a gentleman of great compassion and social conscience, Judge Ogle
founded the Fourth Judicial District Task Force Against Domestic Violence and served as its
president from 1996 to 2000; and
WHEREAS, in recognition of his outstanding service to the judicial system in this area,
Judge Ogle was honored with the Judge Jane Wheatcraft Award by the Tennessee Task Force
Against Domestic Violence; and
WHEREAS, in 1996, he was appointed by the Tennessee Supreme Court to the
Statewide Commission on Foster Care; and
WHEREAS, Judge Ogle has also been active in the Tennessee Judicial Conference,
serving first as Vice President, then President Elect, and finally President for the 2001-2002
term; and
WHEREAS, the son of W. Henry Ogle and Bonnie Huskey Ogle, Judge Ogle is a ninth
generation Tennessean and a native of Sevierville; and
HJR1397
017854
- 1 -

WHEREAS, he received his Bachelor of Arts degree in Political Science from the
University of Tennessee in 1976, graduating with honors, and earned his Juris Doctor from the
Memphis State University Cecil B. Humphreys School of Law in 1979; and
WHEREAS, prior to ascending to the bench, Rex Henry Ogle practiced law in Sevierville
for eleven years as a principal in the firm of Ogle, Wynn and Ogle; during this time, he served as
the attorney for the City of Pigeon Forge and an instructor for the Pigeon Forge Citizens
Academy; and
WHEREAS, a true servant-leader, Judge Ogle has always been active in his community
in a variety of capacities; and
WHEREAS, a graduate of Leadership Sevier, he formerly served as an instructor for the
police departments of the cities of Gatlinburg, Pigeon Forge, and Sevierville; a member of the
Advisory Board for the Lincoln Memorial University School of Law; and Chairman of the Board
of Directors for Museum Appalachia, the Cherish the Child Foundation, and the Sevier County
Public Library Foundation; and
WHEREAS, Judge Ogle gives back to the legal profession as a Fellow of the Tennessee
Bar Foundation and celebrates his heritage as a member of the Tennessee Society Sons of the
Revolution; and
WHEREAS, his many personal and professional accomplishments aside, Rex Henry
Ogle is most grateful for the love and companionship he shares with his wife, Judge Norma
McGee Ogle, who has retired from the Tennessee Court of Criminal Appeals, and his son,
Daniel McGee Ogle, a United Methodist minister serving in Atlanta, Georgia; and
WHEREAS, throughout his illustrious tenure on the bench, Judge Ogle has exhibited the
greatest integrity and a strong commitment to justice, and he is most worthy of our approbation
on this special occasion; now, therefore,
- 2 - 017854

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor Judge Rex Henry Ogle, the longest serving judge in the history
of the Fourth Judicial District, on the occasion of his retirement after thirty-six years on the
Circuit Court bench and extend to him our gratitude for a difficult job well done and our best
wishes for much continued success and happiness.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
